Instructions - start here!

This lab involves the analysis of a longitudinal data set (full details below).

Lets begin by loading the necessary packages and data:

require(lme4)
require(lmerTest)
require(ggplot2)
require(haven)

Overview

The analysis starts by introducing the longitudinal data and some visual representations. This particular dataset was chosen for three primary reasons:

  • It illustrates the basic notion of time in a slightly different context with the hope of a more intuitive understanding. The time variable is age and is continuous (contrary to most cases where it is presented as discrete) to showcase that what defines time is the repeated values within children, rather than a discrete definition and format.

  • It binds well to the notion of covariance. When modelled with a random intercept and random slope model, it has a fanning-out form that is distinct enough to produce a positive covariance, allowing for an intuitive explanation both illustratively and quantitatively of what the sign on a covariance implies.

  • There is a non-linear relationship between the response and time, which presents us with an opportunity to showcase how to deal with it.

The practical continues by comparing the random intercept and full random effects models, again using ggplot2.

It then uses the full random effects model as the primary model to conduct diagnostic checks where non-linearity is discovered in the residuals plot and then remedied using a squared age variable.

It is also shown how one can extract the variance-covariance matrix for inspection and how to use it to build the Intraclass Correlation Coefficient (ICC).

Some basic model assumptions are also tested using visual representations.

Multilevel modelling with longitudinal data

The data set is comprised of child weight for children in a British community who were weighed up to four times, roughly between the ages of 6 weeks and 27 months. (It represents a random sample of data previously analyzed by Goldstein (1986) and Prosser, Rasbash, and Goldstein (1991).)

Download the file childweight.RData from Ultra and place it into your working directory. (Consult Practical 3 if you need further instructions on how to do this.) Then load it into your workspace via ` \(~\)

load("childweight.RData") # Insert directory as needed or save to current working directory
data <- childweight
#Or uncomment the following if there are issues loading the workspace
#data <- read.csv("https://andygolightly.github.io/teaching/MATH43515/childweight.csv")[,-1]

weight <- data$weight      #weight
age <- data$age            #age
birthw <- data$brthwt      #weight at birth 
girl <- data$girl          #indicator (0 for boy and 1 for girl)
id.f <- as.factor(data$id) #individual indicator

TASK: Identify the number of levels in this data set, and the covariate(s) at each level.

Click for solution We have two levels (time nested inside individuals). The age variable is playing the role of time here. Hence, weight, birthw and girl are all at the individual level (top level of the hierarchy).

Empty level model

The empty level model is

\[y_{ti} = \gamma_0 +u_i + \epsilon_{ti}\] which we may fit via

lmodel0 <- lmer(weight ~ 1 + (1 | id), data=data)
## boundary (singular) fit: see help('isSingular')
summary(lmodel0)

In trying to compute ICC we see that \(\hat{\sigma}^2_u=0\). This might suggest that ICC is zero, and that group group structure is not important. However, the empty model asks the question if individuals differ in their average outcome. A more pertinent question in this longitudinal context is if individuals differ in their trajectories over time.

Random intercept model

Lets fit a multilevel model with random intercepts and a binary covariate girl. The model takes the form

\[y_{ti} = a+u_i+ b_1 T_{ti}+b_2\text{girl}_{i} +\epsilon_{ti}\]

We fit the model via:

lmodel <- lmer(weight ~ age  + girl + (1 | id), data=data)
summary(lmodel)

Lets extract and inspect the variance-covariance matrix.

Var_Cov_matrix <- as.data.frame(VarCorr(lmodel2))
Var_Cov_matrix

The positive covariance re-affirms the fanning out pattern observed. The higher the predicted weight at baseline time (that is, higher child intercept), the higher the weight will be as time passes (i.e.a steeper child time slope).

\(~\)

Lets look at a visual comparison between the random intercept vs random intercept and slope model. Make sure you understand the following code:

vars <- c("id","age","weight")

data_pred1 <- cbind(data[,vars],data[,"pred1"],group=1)

data_pred2 <- cbind(data[,vars],data[,"pred2"],group=2)

TASK: Is the random slope on time needed? Perform an appropriate test.

Click for solution

We perform a likelihood ratio test (LRT) via:

ranova(lmodel2)
There is strong evidence to reject the null hypothesis that the slope variance is zero. We need the random slopes!

\(~\)

Dealing with the nonlinear relationship

Given that the more complex model lmodel2 captures non-zero variance in random intercept and slope parameters, we will continue with it as our main model.

Are the model assumptions valid? We will begin by inspecting the residuals.

plot(lmodel2)

It is evident that the plot suggests an underlying non-linear structure.

\(~\)

In order to correct the non-linearity observed, we perform multilevel modelling again, this time including a non-linear term (quadratic) for age.

lmodel3 <- lmer(weight ~ age + c(age*age) + girl  + (1 + age | id), data=data)
summary(lmodel3)
## Linear mixed model fit by REML. t-tests use Satterthwaite's method [

It is evident that the non-linearity has been controlled for and residuals look much more acceptable.

We continue with inspection of model assumptions. i.e.normally distributed residuals and random effects.

qqnorm(resid(lmodel3))

       col = "red")

qqline(ranef(lmodel3)$id[,1],

The QQ Plots also look fairly acceptable (close to y=x line).

Harder: We have not yet included the birth weight birthw variable in the model. How should we interpret the inclusion of birthw as a fixed effect? What would you expect to happen when you include it? Confirm (or deny) your intuition!

Click for solution birthw is an individual level covariate. Hence, its inclusion as a fixed effect may help to explain some of the variability in the random intercept terms. Id expect that adding it in will result in a reduction in the random intercept variance and (probably) an insignificant overall intercept term (since for each individiual, birthw and the random intercept will effectively capture most of the baseline variation.)

\(~\)

Another look at ICC. Having accounted for the nonlinear relationship between age and time, we might wonder what the ICC would look like based on a model of the form

\[y_{ti} = a+u_i+ b_1 T_{ti}+b_2 T_{ti}^2+\epsilon_{ti}\] Fit the model and calculate ICC. Can you explain the change in ICC (compared to that based on the model with a linear term in age only)?

Click for solution

Fit the model with:

lmodel4 <- lmer(weight ~ age + c(age*age) + (1 | id), data=data)
summary(lmodel4)
## Linear mixed model fit by REML. t-tests use Satterthwaite's method [
## lmerModLmerTest]
## Formula: weight ~ age + c(age * age) + (1 | id)
##    Data: data
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: 562.1
## 
## Scaled residuals: 
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.2272 -0.5305  0.0218  0.4756  4.0233 
## 
## Random effects:
##  Groups   Name        Variance Std.Dev.
##  id       (Intercept) 0.8571   0.9258  
##  Residual             0.5478   0.7402  
## Number of obs: 198, groups:  id, 68
## 
## Fixed effects:
##              Estimate Std. Error       df t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)    3.4328     0.1825 177.3122   18.81   <2e-16 ***
## age            7.8180     0.2918 144.5997   26.79   <2e-16 ***
## c(age * age)  -1.7056     0.1094 145.0309  -15.59   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Correlation of Fixed Effects:
##            (Intr) age   
## age        -0.681       
## c(age*age)  0.599 -0.971
for which we can read off an ICC of \(0.8571/(0.8571+0.5478)\) which is 0.61 i.e.much bigger than the earlier ICC of 0.29. This is due to the reduction in residual variance and increase in between group variance, resulting from better describing the relationship between the response and time (age).
